column25:
We severely lack synergy. Our meetings are extremely unproductive. And it's not that we aren't working hard, but we are just working hard in conflicting ideas and goals, so we end up getting nowhere. And it's not like we don't talk about our ideas and goals, in fact, we spend too much time talking about it that it takes up almost the entirety of every meeting, rather than actually working on the assignment. When I bring these issues up, somehow my concerns are ultimately dismissed even if most the group says they agree with it. Then, when completing even the simplest task, it seems like we always decide that to avoid doing double work, we will do triple work in advance. But then the triple work isn't done on time and we end up doing quadruple work later. Our work habits don't mesh well together. I think we should come to meetings more prepared and have more clear, shared goals. Otherwise, I feel like we all might be much more productive independently than in a group together. 

Honestly, I really want to just work alone on this project now, even though I like all the teammates on a personal level, I think we don't really align in how we work or what our goals are. I like working in groups too! But none of my typical strategies at getting a group to work together well is working out. I just don't really know how to improve this group, and I feel like the project and my learning suffers because of it. It already has. It is not a standard simple communication problem or one person slacking off, in fact I think everyone is trying hard-- but the whole group synergy is bad. If everyone agrees to work independently, I'd rather just do that.

Two things rather. First, we need to improve on communication to make sure there's clear alignment on what each member is expected to do. That includes reviewing instructions and rubrics together then brainstorming at a high level the expected results before dividing and conquering. We've had a few instances where we didn't finish tasks by our own team's deadlines due to misalignment. I feel this slows us down and leads to a situation where a few people will have to correct errors closer to the deadline, which disproportionately redistributes work.

Second, I think our team risks developing a "let's just get it done" mindset whenever we don't review the rubric closely. That's something we could think about even though I understand the work/deadlines in this class can somewhat feel overwhelming and so demanding.

column25: I think the team could leverage our meeting times better by being more concrete / targeted on what we need to get done. I think it would be great to drive a bit more structure in our discussions so we know what we're making progress towards vs. having a conversation where the takeaways aren't necessarily clear or tied to what we need to get done next. I think there's also an opportunity for us to define our goals, working styles, and how we can make each other feel more heard. The team has strong opinions which is great, especially as we explore a new space. But we also want to make sure that other individuals on the team feel like their thoughts and concerns are addressed sufficiently.
